When tweets go wrong: Canucks offend own fanbase with well wishes for Blue Jays FOXSports 1 hr ago ¬© Anne-Marie Sorvin-USA TODAY Spor Dec 13, 2014; Vancouver, British Columbia, CAN; Vancouver Canucks forward Alexandre Burrows (14) gets between New York Rangers goaltender Henrik Lundqvist (30) and defenseman Dan Girardi (5) during the third period at Rogers Arena. The New York Rangers won 5-1. Mandatory Credit: Anne-Marie Sorvin-USA TODAY Sports Canadian hockey fans draw battle lines during the NHL season between their seven NHL teams, but it is all One Canada as far as baseball is concerned -- or, it's One Canada until someone tries to bring hockey into the baseball equation.
AdChoices The Canucks' social media team fell victim to the perceived Canadian camraderie on Thursday when the team tried to send well wishes to the Toronto Blue Jays, Canada's lone MLB team, ahead of the Jays' first playoff game in over two decades.
Vancouver's staff decided to send out a tweet warning the Blue Jays against "#RangerDanger", as the Jays will face the Texas Rangers in the ALDS and Vancouver had a bad experience with a different Rangers team -- the New York Rangers -- when the Canucks lost to the Rangers in the 1994 Stanley Cup Finals.
